.doclang {en}

BakingRL is intentionally split across sibling repositories. The split keeps
host code, SDK contracts, and plugin packages independently understandable.

## BakingRL

This repository contains the desktop host:

- Rust/Tauri backend;
- Svelte dashboard and package webview routes;
- telemetry ingestion and runtime routing;
- package installation and state;
- command, service, resource, and sidecar runtime management;
- host documentation.

Host code should not import plugin source directly. Plugins are installed as
packages and accessed through host APIs.

## BakingRLSDK

The SDK repository contains:

- `@bakingrl/plugin-sdk` TypeScript contracts and helpers;
- `@bakingrl/create-plugin` generator and helper CLI;
- plugin manifest and bundle documentation;
- plugin-author guides and examples.

When host behavior changes a public plugin contract, update the SDK docs and
types in the same feature branch.

## BakingRLPlugins

The plugin repository contains first-party and experimental packages. These are
normal plugin packages, not host source. They should be built, validated, and
installed locally through the package helper.

Generated bundles, build outputs, hashes, signatures, and signing keys should
not be committed unless a release process explicitly calls for them.

## BakingRLMarketplace

The Marketplace repository contains the reviewed package index, developer
signing keys, first-run sections, exact release artifact URLs and SHA-256
digests, schemas, validation tests, and the catalogue publication workflow.

The generated public catalogue is signed in CI. Private signing keys never
belong in this or any sibling repository.

## Local Development Flow

Typical runtime testing uses all three repositories:

```txt
BakingRLSDK      update SDK contracts or helper CLI
BakingRLPlugins  rebuild and install packages
BakingRL         reload packages and test host behavior
BakingRLMarketplace  review and publish exact release artifacts
```

Keep commits separate per repository so host, SDK, and plugin changes remain
reviewable.
